extensive marine transgression across the now southern half of the North Island during the Pliocene and early Pleistocene, when there was sea across the present North Island almost as far north as Lake Taupo; however, parts of the southwestern present North Island are thought to have been connected to the northern tip of the South Island at that time, but separated by sea from the rest of the North Island (
Fig. 13
); re-emergence from the sea of the above area, and the closure of all sea connections across central 
New Zealand
during the Pleistocene, at a time of lowered sea levels (
Fig. 14
);

